od(...)` to reach `Class#getMethod(...)`\\n  - `GroovyAssert.notYetImplemented(...)` to reach `Method#invoke(...)`\\n- Updated existing placeholder test class to be explicitly public:\\n  - `Groovy_testTest.groovy`\\n\\nPer instructions, I did not run tests locally.\", \"textSignature\": \"{\\\"v\\\":1,\\\"id\\\":\\\"msg_02539e4073107fc9016a0022573484819cbebf55ac3b75e2b3\\\",\\\"phase\\\":\\\"final_answer\\\"}\"}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 225, \"output\": 609, \"cacheRead\": 14336, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 15170, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"stop\", \"timestamp\": 1778393679552, \"responseId\": \"resp_02539e4073107fc9016a00224fe5f4819cbbd406189167e454\"}, \"toolResults\": []}\n928:[thinking] I need to think through the dynamic access line for `Method#invoke`. It seems that this method might only be recorded if the invocation succeeds, right? If it throws an exception, I'm not sure if the instrumentation would still count it if it throws an `InvocationTargetException`. To handle this properly, I guess the `Method.invoke` needs to return normally. But what if it throws an `AssertionError`? Can we catch that outside? This requires some careful handling!\n934:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering method invocation**\\n\\nI need to think through the dynamic access line for `Method#invoke`. It seems that this method might only be recorded if the invocation succeeds, right? If it throws an exception, I'm not sure if the instrumentation would still count it if it throws an `InvocationTargetException`. To handle this properly, I guess the `Method.invoke` needs to return normally. But what if it throws an `AssertionError`? Can we catch that outside? This requires some careful handling!\", \"thinkingSignatu